up its <PLACE country="US" form="NOM" id="Pl-12" state="US-PA" type="FAC">airport</PLACE> complete with a sprawling retail <PLACE country="US" form="NOM" id="Pl-13" state="US-PA" type="FAC">complex</PLACE> in the <PLACE country="US" form="NOM" id="Pl-14" state="US-PA" type="FAC">terminal</PLACE>.
Now <PLACE country="US" form="NAM" gazref="IGDB:840" id="Pl-4" predicative="true" state="US-PA" type="COUNTRY">US</PLACE> Airways has reduced flights out of <PLACE country="US" form="NAM" gazref="IGDB:1214644" id="Pl-8" latLong="40.441째N 79.996째W" state="US-PA" type="PPL">Pittsburgh</PLACE> by 28% since
January of 2004 and is in real danger of folding completely. These shiny
new airports are usually financed by long-term bonds that still have to
paid off...but not by the airlines.

This is an industry looking for a sustainable strategy. <PLACE country="US" form="NAM" gazref="IGDB:840" id="Pl-5" mod="SW" predicative="true" type="COUNTRY">Southwest</PLACE> and
JetBlue were the only major airlines to earn a profit in 2004 but who
